Guided Exercise: Install Operators Using the Web Console
Objective of the Lab
In this lab you will:
1.	Install an operator from OperatorHub
2.	Observe resources created by Operator Lifecycle Manager (OLM)
3.	Create a Custom Resource
4.	See how the operator creates workloads automatically
5.	Uninstall the operator
________________________________________
1️⃣ Prepare the Lab Environment
Run:
lab start operators-web
What this command does
It prepares the training cluster environment:
•	Starts required lab services
•	Ensures cluster connectivity
•	Creates required resources
•	Resets environment for this exercise
So you start with a clean cluster environment.
________________________________________
2️⃣ Login to the OpenShift Web Console
Open browser:
https://console-openshift-console.apps.ocp4.example.com
Login credentials:
username: admin
password: redhatocp
Choose Red Hat Identity Management authentication.
________________________________________
3️⃣ Install the File Integrity Operator
Go to:
Operators → OperatorHub
Search:
integrity
Select:
File Integrity Operator
Click:
Install
________________________________________
4️⃣ Operator Installation Options (Used in the Lab)
Update Channel
Only one channel is available because the lab cluster is disconnected.
Disconnected cluster means:
•	No internet
•	Operators come from a mirror registry
Mirror registry = local copy of container images.
________________________________________
Installation Mode
Default option:
All namespaces on the cluster
Meaning:
The operator monitors all namespaces for custom resources.
________________________________________
Installed Namespace
Operator will run in:
openshift-file-integrity
Important difference:
Component	Location
Operator workload	openshift-file-integrity namespace
Resources it monitors	All namespaces
________________________________________
Monitoring
Do NOT enable monitoring in this lab.
Monitoring would integrate the operator with cluster monitoring stack.
________________________________________
Start Installation
Click:
Install
OLM now installs the operator.
________________________________________
5️⃣ What OLM Creates During Installation
When you install an operator, OLM automatically creates resources.
Main resources:
Resource	Purpose
Subscription	Controls operator updates
InstallPlan	Defines installation steps
ClusterServiceVersion (CSV)	Operator version description
OperatorGroup	Defines watched namespaces
You can verify them using CLI.
________________________________________
Check CSV
oc get csv -n openshift-file-integrity
Example output:
file-integrity-operator.v1.0.0   Succeeded
Meaning installation finished successfully.
________________________________________
Check Subscription
oc get subscription -n openshift-file-integrity
Shows update channel configuration.
________________________________________
Check InstallPlan
oc get installplan -n openshift-file-integrity
Defines installation steps executed by OLM.
________________________________________
Check Operator Pods
oc get pods -n openshift-file-integrity
Example:
file-integrity-operator-xxxxx
This is the operator controller.
________________________________________
6️⃣ Operator Details Page
After installation click:
View Operator
Important tabs:
________________________________________
Details Tab
Shows:
•	Operator version
•	Description
•	CSV information
Scroll to Conditions.
Important status:
Succeeded
Meaning installation completed.
________________________________________
YAML Tab
Displays the ClusterServiceVersion YAML.
Equivalent command:
oc get csv -n openshift-file-integrity -o yaml
CSV describes:
•	Operator version
•	APIs supported
•	deployments
•	permissions
________________________________________
Subscription Tab
Shows:
•	Update channel
•	Update approval
•	InstallPlan
Command:
oc get subscription -n openshift-file-integrity
If update approval is manual, you approve updates here.
________________________________________
7️⃣ Creating a Custom Resource
Operators are used through Custom Resources (CR).
The File Integrity Operator manages:
FileIntegrity
resource.
Go to:
File Integrity tab
Click:
Create FileIntegrity
________________________________________
YAML Configuration
Modify:
gracePeriod: 60
Example YAML:
apiVersion: fileintegrity.openshift.io/v1alpha1
kind: FileIntegrity
metadata:
  name: example-fileintegrity
spec:
  gracePeriod: 60
Meaning:
Operator checks node filesystem every 60 seconds.
________________________________________
8️⃣ What the Operator Does After CR Creation
Once the CR is created, the operator automatically:
1.	Creates DaemonSet
2.	Runs file integrity check on nodes
3.	Generates reports
________________________________________
Check Node Status
Go to:
FileIntegrityNodeStatus tab
Example resource:
example-fileintegrity-master01
This shows file verification results for nodes.
________________________________________
9️⃣ Simulate File System Change
Now you intentionally modify node filesystem.
Login to cluster:
oc login -u admin -p redhatocp https://api.ocp4.example.com:6443
________________________________________
Debug Node
Run:
oc debug node/master01 -- touch /host/etc/foobar
Explanation:
Part	Meaning
oc debug	start debug container
node/master01	target node
touch /host/etc/foobar	create new file
This changes node filesystem.
Operator should detect this change.
________________________________________
🔟 View Integrity Report
Go to:
Workloads → ConfigMaps
Namespace:
openshift-file-integrity
Search:
example
Open:
aide-example-fileintegrity-master01-failed
Inside Data section you see report showing:
file changes detected
Meaning operator detected filesystem modification.
________________________________________
1️⃣1️⃣ Understand Operator Workloads vs Managed Workloads
This is a very important exam concept.
________________________________________
Operator Workload
Go to:
Workloads → Deployments
Deployment:
file-integrity-operator
This deployment:
•	watches custom resources
•	manages workloads
________________________________________
Operator Managed Workload
Go to:
Workloads → DaemonSets
Example:
aide-example-fileintegrity
Created automatically after you created FileIntegrity CR.
Purpose:
Run integrity checks on every node.
________________________________________
Why DaemonSet?
Because file integrity must run on every node.
DaemonSet ensures:
1 pod per node
________________________________________
1️⃣2️⃣ Uninstall the Operator
Go to:
Operators → Installed Operators
Select:
File Integrity Operator
Click:
Actions → Uninstall Operator
Enable option:
Delete all operand instances
Operand = resources created by operator.
Example:
FileIntegrity CR
DaemonSets
________________________________________
1️⃣3️⃣ Delete the Namespace
Operator created namespace:
openshift-file-integrity
Delete it:
Home → Projects
Search:
openshift-file-integrity
Delete project.
